$ PowerShell cmdLet split-path

The `split-path` cmdLet allows to select parts such as directories, filenames or extensions from a path. The cmdLet returns strings.

The value that is returned dependes on the option that is pass to split-path. With the example of *drive:\dirOne\dirTwo\file.ext*, the following parts of the path are returned:
table { lll
  ~Option used~  ☰ ~Returned value~ ☰ ~Comment~
                 ☰ drive:\dirOne\dirTwo ☰
  `-parent`      ☰ drive:\dirOne\dirTwo ☰ Requires PowerShell 6 or later
  `-leaf`        ☰ file.ext ☰
  `-leafBase`    ☰ file ☰
  `-extension`   ☰ .ext ☰ Requires PowerShell 6 or later
  `-qualifier`   ☰ drive: ☰
  `-noQualifier` ☰ \dirOne\dirTwo\file.ext ☰
  `-isAbsolute`  ☰ → Windows/PowerShell/language/variable/automatic/true-false[$true] ☰
table }

These results were obtained with the following test script:
gh|about-PowerShell|/cmdlets/path/split/go.ps1||

sa:

  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/path
